               <msContents>
                  
                  <msItem class="#theologica" n="1" xml:id="MS_Bodl_812-item1">
                     <locus>(fol. 1)</locus>
                     <title key="work_14812" rend="italic" type="desc">Summa theologica</title>
                     <explicit>Expliciunt sermones a Natiuitate Domini vsque ad Aduentum, de Tempore</explicit>
                     <note>The first 24 leaves (18 1/2 sermons) are lost, and the text begins 'gaudet sancta anima'. The next sermon
                        begins 'Vincere in bono malum ... Duces exercitus'. About 107 sermons are left</note>
                     
                     <note>At fol. 137v are two indexes of subjects, partly on erased writings,
                     and at fol. 243v yet another (added) index of subjects, entitled
                     'Kalendarium siue concordancie super Summam Abiciamus per ordinem
                     alpbabeti'</note> 
                     
                     <note>The texts are sometimes followed by a French translation, as on fol. 123</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                 
                  <msItem n="2" xml:id="MS_Bodl_812-item2">
                     <locus>(fol. 139)</locus>
                     <author key="person_249874164">Nicholas de Byard</author>
                     <title key="work_3288">Summa de abstinentia</title>
                     <rubric>Distincciones Parisiensis de modo predicandi</rubric>
                     <incipit>De abstinencia. Duplex est abstinencia, detestabilis &amp; laudabilis</incipit>
                     <note>At the head is: 'Sunt hoc collecta libro uulgalia multa. Ex alphabeto distincte
                     scripta teneto. Et positum titulo quodlibet est proprio'</note>
                     <note>At fol. 239 follow 'Adaptaciones omnium sermonum in hoc libello [sc. in Distinctionibus
                     supradictis] contentorum prout competunt sabbatis dominicis &amp; feriis
                     tocius anni', and a list of the 134 chapters</note>
                     <textLang mainLang="la">Latin</textLang>
                  </msItem>
                
                  <msItem><p>There are several sets of numberings of the columns and leaves of this
                     volume</p></msItem>
                  
